\title{Optimism on a Moving Subspace:\\Priced-Probe Identification for Piecewise Low-Rank Bandits}

\author{%
  Anonymous Authors%
}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
In linear contextual bandits whose reward parameter
$\theta_t\in\R^d$ lies in a rank-$r$ subspace ($r\ll d$) that changes
at unknown changepoints, low-rank methods assume a fixed
representation while nonstationary methods pay the full ambient
$\tilO(d\sqrt T)$. The obstacle is information-theoretic: a
single-play scalar reward is a rank-one measurement of a rank-$r$
subspace, so the structure cannot be recovered through passive
exploration. We resolve this by pricing a probe channel and routing
its feedback through the lifted moment
$\E[(y_t^2-\hat\sigma^2)\,u_tu_t^\top] = \mathcal K(\widetilde M_t)$,
turning rank-one rewards into matrix-valued samples whose
eigenstructure the algorithm recovers exactly under isotropic Gaussian
probes (the plugin-variance bias is a scaled identity, so eigenvectors
are preserved). The resulting algorithm SPSC (Single-Play
Subspace-Calibrated Optimism) interleaves probes with projected
ridge-UCB in a learned $r$-dim subspace and attains costed dynamic
regret $\tilO(r\sqrt{KT})+\tilO(d^{2/3}K^{1/3}T^{2/3})$ in the
piecewise-constant regime with sample-variance estimation
(Theorem~\ref{thm:spsc_regret} states the full bound with explicit
path-variation and variance-misspecification terms);
a matching $\Omega(c^{1/3}T^{2/3})$ lower bound holds for all
bounded-action policies with isotropic Gaussian probes (no
projection-class restriction), and the three probe-side conditions
are individually necessary. On nine synthetic, real-data, and
clinical benchmarks covering both exactly rank-$r$ and approximately
low-rank subspaces, SPSC reduces regret over LinUCB and the strongest
non-oracle baselines wherever the gap $d-r\gtrsim d^{2/3}(T/K)^{1/6}$
holds, validating the crossover our theory predicts.
\end{abstract}


%% ============================================================
\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

High-dimensional sequential decision problems such as personalized
recommendation, clinical dosing, and targeted scientific
experimentation share two properties that the linear-bandit
literature has so far
handled only in isolation. First, the reward parameter $\theta_t\in\R^d$
typically admits a \emph{low-rank} factorisation $\theta_t=B_k^\star w_t$
with $r\ll d$: user tastes, drug--response pathways, and policy-sensitive
feature directions live on a thin slice of the ambient space. Second,
that thin slice is \emph{not static}: tastes drift, cohorts change,
treatment regimes get revised, and the subspace $\range(B_k^\star)$
itself moves across unknown changepoints. The learner sees only a
scalar reward $y_t=x_t^\top\theta_t+\varepsilon_t$, so the low-rank
structure can neither be read off nor refreshed from direct
observations of $\theta_t$.

Existing work treats exactly one of the two properties.
Stationary low-rank
bandits~\citep{jun2019bilinear,pmlr-v235-jedra24a,lu2021lowrank}
deliver the desired $\tilO(r\sqrt T)$ rate but assume a fixed $B^\star$,
which the first subspace change in real data invalidates.
Nonstationary bandits~\citep{russac2019weighted,cheung2019learning}
adapt to drifting parameters but pay the full ambient rate
$\tilO(d\sqrt T)$ and do not exploit intrinsic rank. Closing this gap is
delicate: with scalar feedback, a single response $y_t$ is a rank-one
measurement of $\theta_t\theta_t^\top$, so the subspace can only be
recovered through \emph{second-order} probing, and every probe diverts
a round away from exploitation, which must itself be priced. No prior
algorithm recovers a changing subspace under scalar feedback, and no
prior analysis prices that recovery against the exploitation regret it
enables.

At each round $t = 1,\dots,T$ the learner picks $x_t \in \cA_t
\subset \R^d$ and observes $y_t = x_t^\top \theta_t + \varepsilon_t$,
where $\theta_t = B_k^\star w_t$ for some unknown orthonormal
$B_k^\star \in \R^{d\times r}$ that is piecewise constant across $K$
segments, and $w_t$ follows a stable latent LDS $w_t = A_k w_{t-1} +
\eta_{t-1}$ inside each segment. Performance is measured by the
\emph{costed dynamic regret}
\begin{equation}
\DynReg_T^{(c)} := \sum_{t\notin\cTprobe} \Bigl(\max_{x\in\cA_t} x^\top \theta_t
  - x_t^\top \theta_t\Bigr) + c\,|\cTprobe|,
\label{eq:intro_costed_regret}
\end{equation}
which sums action-gap regret over exploitation rounds and charges a
flat per-probe cost $c$ for each designated probe round
$t\in\cTprobe\subseteq[T]$, where the learner plays $x_t = u_t$
drawn from a fixed probe distribution $Q$ (potentially unbounded;
$u_t$ need not lie in $\cA_t$). This convention treats probes as a
priced observation channel rather than a within-action choice; the
per-probe cost $c$ implicitly absorbs the foregone-reward upper
bound $2 R_\cA S_w$ that any non-probing baseline could achieve on
that round, so $c$ should be calibrated to reflect both the
exploration cost and the foregone exploit value.

Scalar feedback makes subspace recovery nontrivial: a single
$y_t = x_t^\top B_k^\star w_t + \varepsilon_t$ is a scalar projection
of a rank-$r$ signal, so only \emph{second-order} information reveals
$\range(B_k^\star)$. And priced probing creates a
tradeoff, more probes reduce subspace error $O(1/\sqrt{m})$ but
add cost $O(cm)$, whose optimum determines the leading
rate.

\paragraph{Contributions.}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=1.5em,itemsep=2pt]
\item \textbf{Algorithm.} We introduce \textbf{SPSC}
(Alg.~\ref{alg:spsc}), which interleaves probing
with windowed projected ridge-UCB inside the learned
$r$-dimensional subspace. A \textbf{SPSC-Adaptive}
variant (Alg.~\ref{alg:spsc_adaptive})
uses a CUSUM-style detector on the lifted probe moment to discover
segment changes online; under detector-separation
$\Delta_k\ge 2b$ and admissible window $W_{\mathrm{det}}$, it
matches the oracle-boundary leading rate using only macroscopic
$K,T$ instead of per-segment boundaries.
\item \textbf{Regret.} Suppressing polylog factors and under exact
probes ($\hat\sigma^2=\sigma_\varepsilon^2$ and $\epsilon_\times=0$),
\[
\DynReg_T^{(c)} = \tilO\!\bigl(r\sqrt{KT}\bigr)+\tilO\!\bigl(d^{2/3}K^{1/3}T^{2/3}\bigr)+O(WV),
\]
where the \emph{leading} exploitation term replaces ambient
$d\sqrt{KT}$ with intrinsic rank $r$. (An additional
$O(T\Delta_\sigma)$ bias floor under inexact probes.)
For any policy with bounded exploit actions and isotropic Gaussian
probes (no projection-class restriction; this class contains every
algorithm in our empirical comparison), we prove an
$\Omega(c^{1/3}T^{2/3})$ regret lower bound on the probe-acquisition
term (Theorem~\ref{thm:spsc_lb}, in the regime $d\gtrsim T^{1/3}$).
This matches the upper bound in $T$ on the probe-acquisition term;
matching the leading $r\sqrt{KT}$ exploit-regret term outside the
projection class, and tightness in $d$ on the probe-term prefactor,
remain open. Self-contained proofs of all main-text statements
appear in Appendix~\ref{app:proofs}.
\item \textbf{Experiments.} We evaluate SPSC on a synthetic
phase-transition grid and on eight real-data and semi-synthetic
clinical benchmarks (UCI Covertype, Pendigits, Satimage, MNIST,
Fashion-MNIST, MovieLens; Warfarin and Vancomycin clinical dosing),
against 11 baselines: LinUCB, D-LinUCB, SW-LinUCB, Restart-LinUCB,
LowOFUL, VOFUL, LowRank-Reward, LinTS~\citep{agrawal2013thompson},
SW-LinTS, and two adapted stationary low-rank methods (BOSS, Jedra).
SPSC delivers $13$--$34\%$ regret reductions on the synthetic grid;
on real-data benchmarks the best-cell reductions vs.\ the strongest
non-oracle baseline range from $0$--$60\%$ across cells, with the
largest wins ($\ge 30\%$) on Pendigits, Satimage, MNIST, and the
clinical datasets, while approximately low-rank cells (e.g.\
MovieLens) show smaller reductions (precise theoretical boundary
$d - r \gtrsim d^{2/3}(T/K)^{1/6}$, Theorem~\ref{thm:spsc_regret}).
\end{enumerate}

\paragraph{Related work.}
Stationary low-rank
bandits~\citep{jun2019bilinear,kang2022gestt,pmlr-v235-jedra24a,pmlr-v235-jang24e,stojanovic2023spectral}
achieve intrinsic-rank rates but assume a fixed $B^\star$.
Nonstationary
bandits~\citep{russac2019weighted,cheung2019learning,abbasi2023dynamic,hou2024pslb}
bound dynamic regret in $d$ and do not exploit low-rank structure.
Cost-aware
observation~\citep{seldin2014paid,tucker2023costly,elumar2025costly}
prices information acquisition but targets fixed parameters, not
identifying a changing subspace. SPSC is the first algorithm we
are aware of that (i) attains regret scaling with intrinsic
rank $r$, (ii) adapts to changing subspaces without oracle boundaries,
and (iii) prices the cost of probe acquisition explicitly.

%% ============================================================
\section{Setting and probe-based identification}
\label{sec:setting}

\paragraph{Piecewise low-rank model.}
At every round $t$ the reward parameter admits a factorisation
$\theta_t = B_k^\star w_t$, where $B_k^\star \in \R^{d\times r}$ has
orthonormal columns and is piecewise constant over $K\ge 1$ segments
$\cI_k$ with unknown change points
$1=\tau_0<\tau_1<\dots<\tau_K\le T{+}1$. The latent state $w_t\in\R^r$
is piecewise constant within each segment up to bounded total drift
$V := \sum_k \sum_{s\in\cI_k}\|w_{s+1}-w_s\|_2$ (our theory is
informative when $V = o(r\sqrt{KT}/W)$; concretely when boundary jumps
dominate and within-segment motion is small, as is typical in the
benchmarks we study). A natural generating mechanism is the
stable-LDS special case
\[
 w_t = A_k w_{t-1} + \eta_{t-1}, \qquad t \in \cI_k,
\]
with unknown $A_k$ satisfying $\rho(A_k)\le 1{-}\alpha_0$ and zero-mean
innovation $\eta_{t-1}$ with covariance $\Sigma_{\eta,k}\succ 0$
(which produces piecewise constant $w_t$ in the low-innovation limit
and bounded per-step drift otherwise). We
assume uniform action-boundedness $\sup_{x\in\cA_t}\|x\|\le R_\cA$,
a known probe distribution $Q$ with $\E[uu^\top]\succeq \rho I_d$ and
sub-Gaussian marginals (bounded $\|u\|\le L$ is a special case; see
Remark~\ref{rem:subgauss_probe}), conditionally
$\sigma_\varepsilon$-sub-Gaussian noise with
$\E[\varepsilon_t^2\mid\cH_{t-1}]=\sigma_\varepsilon^2$ a.s.\
(homoscedastic conditional variance, estimated online), conditionally
bounded state--noise coupling
$\|\E[\varepsilon_t\theta_t\mid\cH_{t-1}]\|_2 \le \epsilon_\times$
a.s., and full-dimensional probe coverage. These three probe-side
conditions are sufficient and natural for identifying the changing
subspace from single-play scalar rewards; weakening any of them
materially complicates the identifiability picture (e.g., heteroscedastic
noise breaks the $y_t^2-\hat\sigma^2$ unbiasedness used in
Lemma~\ref{lem:G_unbiased_conf}).

\begin{remark}[Sub-Gaussian probes]
\label{rem:subgauss_probe}
The analysis is stated with almost-surely bounded probes to apply
matrix Bernstein directly; isotropic Gaussian probes used in the
experiments satisfy $\|u\|_2\le L:=\sqrt{2d\log(T/\delta)}$ on a
probability-$1{-}\delta/T$ event, so truncating at this threshold and
union-bounding over probe rounds costs at most an additive $\delta$ in
the failure probability and an extra $\sqrt{\log(T/\delta)}$ factor in
constants, leaving the $\tilO(\cdot)$ rate unchanged. See
Appendix~\ref{app:truncation} for the formal statement.
\end{remark}

\paragraph{Assumptions (A1--A4).}
The analysis relies on four conditions, made explicit here so they
can be cited directly by the theorems below:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.5em,nosep]
\item[\textbf{(A1)}] \emph{Probe coverage:} the probe distribution
  $Q$ satisfies $\E[uu^\top]\succeq\rho I_d$ for some $\rho>0$, with
  sub-Gaussian marginals. When the per-round action set $\cA_t$
  spans only a proper subspace $\mathcal V_t\subsetneq\R^d$ (e.g., finite or
  low-rank action sets), $Q$ is restricted to $\mathcal V_t$ and the coverage
  condition reads
  $\E[u_t u_t^\top\mid u_t\in\mathcal V_t]\succeq\rho\,\Pi_{\mathcal V_t}$,
  where $\Pi_{\mathcal V_t}$ is the orthogonal projector onto $\mathcal V_t$ and
  $\rho>0$ depends only on $\dim\mathcal V_t$ and the conditioning of $\cA_t$;
  all subsequent identification and regret guarantees apply with $d$
  replaced by $\dim\mathcal V_t$ in the probe-term constants.
\item[\textbf{(A2)}] \emph{Homoscedastic conditional noise:}
  $\E[\varepsilon_t^2\mid\cH_{t-1}]=\sigma_\varepsilon^2$ a.s., with
  $\sigma_\varepsilon^2$ either known or consistently estimated online.
\item[\textbf{(A3)}] \emph{Bounded state--noise coupling, $u$-independent:}
  $\|\E[\varepsilon_t\theta_t\mid\cH_{t-1},u_t]\|_2\le\epsilon_\times$
  a.s.\ on probe rounds, and the coupling vector
  $\E[\varepsilon_t\theta_t\mid\cH_{t-1},u_t] = \E[\varepsilon_t\theta_t\mid\cH_{t-1}]$
  does not depend on $u_t$. This is automatic when $u_t$ is drawn
  freshly from a fixed probe distribution $Q$ independent of
  $(\theta_t,\varepsilon_t)\mid\cH_{t-1}$, the standard
  exploration-channel setup; we state it explicitly because the
  Gaussian odd-moment cancellation in
  Lemma~\ref{lem:G_unbiased_conf} requires it.
\item[\textbf{(A4)}] \emph{Persistent latent excitation:} within each
  segment $\cI_k$,
  $\lambda_r\bigl(m_k^{-1}\sum_{t\in\cT_k}\E[w_tw_t^\top\mid\cH_{t-1}]\bigr)\ge\lambda_{\min}>0$.
\end{itemize}
(A1)--(A3) are sufficient \emph{and individually necessary}: dropping
any one of them makes the conditional second moment $\widetilde M_t$
unidentifiable from the observable $y_t^2-\hat\sigma^2$
(Propositions~\ref{prop:nonid_a}--\ref{prop:nonid_c} in
Appendix~\ref{app:necessity}, with two-instance constructions in
each case). The assumptions are not chosen for analytical convenience;
they are the weakest conditions under which subspace identification
from single-play scalar feedback is possible at all. (A4) is the
``persistence of excitation'' condition standard in adaptive control,
holding automatically for the stable-LDS generator under
non-degenerate innovation covariance, and failing in degenerate cases
(e.g., $w_t$ confined to a proper subspace of $\R^r$).

\paragraph{Applicability and probe feasibility.}
Probes model an explicit \emph{exploration channel}, separate from
the exploitation catalog $\cA_t$, in which the learner deploys $u_t\sim Q$
in place of an exploitation choice, paying cost $c$. The channel is
natural in experimental design, A/B testing with randomised-item
slots, randomised clinical-dosing protocols, and recommenders with
exploration slots; deployments without such a channel are out of
scope. For a discrete catalog, the theory applies on
$\mathrm{span}(\cA_t)$: recovery targets the projection of
$\range(B_k^\star)$ onto the action span (the only subspace relevant
to regret against feasible actions); the constant $\rho$ in (A1) then
depends on the conditioning of $\cA_t$.

\paragraph{Quadratic measurement identity.}
Let $\hat\sigma^2$ be the algorithm's estimate of the noise variance
and define the centred probe statistic $s_t := y_t^2 - \hat\sigma^2$
on every probe round $t\in\cTprobe$. Under Assumptions (A1)--(A3) on the probe
noise, for $\delta_\sigma := \hat\sigma^2-\sigma_\varepsilon^2$,
\begin{equation}
\E[s_t \mid \cH_{t-1},u_t]
  = u_t^\top \widetilde{M}_t u_t + 2 u_t^\top
    \E[\varepsilon_t\theta_t\mid\cH_{t-1},u_t] - \delta_\sigma,
\label{eq:quad_identity}
\end{equation}
where $\widetilde{M}_t := \E[\theta_t\theta_t^\top\mid \cH_{t-1}]$
is the predictable second moment, whose range equals $\range(B_k^\star)$
for $t\in\cI_k$. Under exact probe conditions
($\delta_\sigma = \epsilon_\times = 0$) this collapses to
$\E[s_t\mid\cdot] = u_t^\top\widetilde M_t u_t$: \emph{a scalar reward
carries a quadratic measurement of $\widetilde M_t$}.

\paragraph{Lifted subspace estimator.}
The probe moment operator $\mathcal K : M \mapsto \E[(u^\top M u)\,uu^\top]$
is invertible on symmetric matrices whenever $Q$'s fourth-moment tensor is
non-degenerate (e.g.\ isotropic Gaussian or spherical probes). Define the
\emph{lifted probe sample}
\begin{equation}
G_t := \mathcal K^{-1}(s_t\,u_tu_t^\top),\qquad
\E[G_t\mid \cH_{t-1}] = \widetilde M_t + \widetilde B_t,
\label{eq:lifted_sample}
\end{equation}
with bias $\|\widetilde B_t\|_\op \le |\delta_\sigma|\,L^2
+ 2L^3\epsilon_\times$ for general bounded probes (using $\|\mathcal
K^{-1}\|_\op \le 1$ from Lemma~\ref{lem:K_inverse}, valid for
Gaussian probes; for general non-degenerate probe distributions $Q$
the same form applies up to a $Q$-dependent constant
$\kappa_{\mathcal K}$). Under isotropic Gaussian probes the bias is
exactly $-\delta_\sigma/(d+2)\,I_d$, a scaled identity that does not
rotate eigenvectors (Lemma~\ref{lem:G_unbiased_conf}). Averaging lifted samples across
the probe rounds of segment $k$ yields
$\widehat M_k := m_k^{-1}\sum_{t\in\cT_k} G_t$, whose top-$r$ eigenvectors
form $\widehat U_k\in\R^{d\times r}$ with
$\|\widehat P_k - P_k^\star\|_\op \le C_{\mathrm{sub}}\sqrt{\log(d/\delta)/m_k}$
(Theorem~\ref{thm:spsc_regret} below).
For isotropic Gaussian probes the variance misspecification bias
$\widetilde B$ is a scaled identity, so it shifts eigenvalues uniformly
and \emph{does not rotate eigenvectors}, subspace recovery is robust to
the plugin estimate of $\sigma_\varepsilon^2$.

%% ============================================================
\section{Algorithm}
\label{sec:algorithm}

SPSC (Alg.~\ref{alg:spsc}) operates in two phases per segment $k$:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.5em,nosep]
\item \textbf{Probe block} (the first $m_k$ rounds of segment $k$):
draw $u_t\sim Q$, play $x_t=u_t$, observe $y_t$, and accumulate
$G_t$ into $\widehat M_k$. After $m_k$ probes, set
$\widehat U_k = \TopEig_r(m_k^{-1}\widehat M_k)$ and freeze it for
the rest of the segment.
\item \textbf{Exploitation phase} ($t \in E_k$, the remaining
$n_k = \ell_k - m_k$ rounds): project each action $x\in\cA_t$ to
$z_t(x) = \widehat U_k^\top x\in\R^r$, maintain a per-segment
cumulative ridge-UCB estimate
$\widehat a_t = V_t^{-1} b_t$ over $V_t = \lambda I_r +
\sum_{s\in E_k, s<t} z_s z_s^\top$ (reset at each segment boundary),
and play $x_t = \argmax_{x\in\cA_t} \bigl\{z_t(x)^\top\widehat a_t
+ \widetilde\beta_{k,t}\|z_t(x)\|_{V_t^{-1}}
+ \gamma_k \|x\|_2 \bigr\}$.
\end{itemize}
The two-phase per-segment structure makes the projector
$\widehat U_k$ constant during exploitation (load-bearing for the
proof, Step~(i.b) of \S\ref{app:proof_main}); the interleaved
implementation used in our experiments refreshes $\widehat U_t$
online and is described in App.~\ref{app:adaptive_algo}. The
algorithmic (``inflated'') confidence radius
$\widetilde\beta_{k,t} := \beta_{k,t}+\bar V_k\sqrt{n_k}+R_\cA S_w\bar\varepsilon_k\sqrt{2 n_k r L_k}$
uses the \emph{deterministic} drift budget
$\bar V_k := 2R_\cA S_w$ (valid in the piecewise-constant
within-segment regime, where the only drift edge is the segment
boundary), and the \emph{computable} subspace-error upper bound
$\bar\varepsilon_k := C_{\mathrm{sub}}\sqrt{\log(2d/\delta)/m_k} + \bar\Delta_\sigma$
from Cor.~\ref{cor:projector_conf}, which is a high-probability
upper bound on the unobservable
$\varepsilon_k = \|\widehat P_k - P_k^\star\|_\op$. The
\emph{base statistical radius}
$\beta_{k,t} = \sigma_\varepsilon\sqrt{r\log(1+n_k R_\cA^2/(\lambda r))+2\log(1/\delta)}+\sqrt\lambda\,S_w$
scales with $\sqrt r$, not $\sqrt d$: this is where the
intrinsic-rank improvement enters. The correction
$\gamma_k = S_w\bar\varepsilon_k$ handles the raw
subspace-mismatch bias
$|x^\top(I-\widehat P_k)\theta|\le R_\cA S_w\varepsilon_k$ via
$\gamma_k\|x\|_2\le R_\cA\gamma_k$. Per-round cost during
exploitation is $O(dr|\cA_t|+r^2)$ (one $\widehat U_k^\top x$ per
candidate plus an $r\times r$ ridge update); per-round cost during
probes is $O(d^2)$ for the lifted moment update. Cumulative cost
across a segment is therefore $O(m_k d^2 + n_k(dr|\cA_t|+r^2))$,
matching ambient LinUCB's $O(\ell_k d^2|\cA_t|)$ up to an
$O(d/r)$ speed-up in the exploitation phase.

\begin{algorithm}[H]
  \caption{\textbf{SPSC}: Single-Play Subspace-Calibrated Optimism (oracle boundaries, front-loaded probes)}
  \label{alg:spsc}
  \begin{algorithmic}[1]
  \footnotesize
  \State \textbf{Input:} segments $\{\cI_k\}_{k=1}^K$ with $\cI_k=\{\tau_{k-1},\dots,\tau_k-1\}$,
         probe budgets $\{m_k\}_{k=1}^K$, $\lambda{>}0$, probe distribution $Q$,
         rank $r$, plug-in noise variance $\hat\sigma^2$, action bound $R_\cA$, parameter bound $S_w$,
         confidence $\delta$.
  \For{segment $k=1,\dots,K$}
      \State $\widehat M_k\leftarrow 0$;\ \ $V\leftarrow \lambda I_r$;\ \ $b\leftarrow 0$.
      \For{$t=\tau_{k-1},\dots,\tau_{k-1}+m_k-1$}\Comment{probe block ($m_k$ rounds)}
          \State draw $u_t\sim Q$; play $x_t=u_t$; observe $y_t$.
          \State $s_t \leftarrow y_t^2 - \hat\sigma^2$;\
                 $G_t \leftarrow \mathcal K^{-1}(s_t\,u_tu_t^\top)$;\
                 $\widehat M_k \leftarrow \widehat M_k + G_t$.
      \EndFor
      \State $\widehat U_k \leftarrow \TopEig_r(\widehat M_k/m_k)$.\Comment{freeze for the segment}
      \State Compute $\bar\varepsilon_k\leftarrow C_{\mathrm{sub}}\sqrt{\log(2d/\delta)/m_k}+\bar\Delta_\sigma$.
      \For{$t=\tau_{k-1}+m_k,\dots,\tau_k-1$}\Comment{exploitation phase}
          \State $z_t(x)\leftarrow \widehat U_k^\top x$ for $x\in\cA_t$;\
                 $\widehat a_t \leftarrow V^{-1}b$.
          \State $x_t \leftarrow \argmax_{x\in\cA_t}\bigl\{
                  z_t(x)^\top\widehat a_t + \widetilde\beta_{k,t}\|z_t(x)\|_{V^{-1}}
                  + \gamma_k\|x\|_2 \bigr\}$.
          \State observe $y_t$;\ \ $V\leftarrow V + z_t(x_t)z_t(x_t)^\top$;\
                 $b\leftarrow b + z_t(x_t)\,y_t$.
      \EndFor
  \EndFor
  \end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\paragraph{Adaptive variant (unknown boundaries).}
SPSC-Adaptive replaces the oracle changepoint schedule with a
two-window CUSUM-style detector on the lifted probe moment, triggering
a subspace reset when the recent and past windows diverge beyond a
calibrated threshold. Theorem~\ref{thm:spsc_adaptive} below gives the
formal hypotheses and regret bound; full pseudocode and analysis are
in Appendix~\ref{app:adaptive_algo}.

%% ============================================================
\section{Regret guarantees}
\label{sec:theory}

\begin{theorem}[Costed dynamic regret of SPSC]
\label{thm:spsc_regret}
Under (A1)--(A4) of \S\ref{sec:setting} with \emph{isotropic
Gaussian probes} (our default; the general case is in
Remark~\ref{rem:general_probes}), run Alg.~\ref{alg:spsc}
with probe allocation $m_k = \lceil (B\ell_k/(2A))^{2/3}\rceil$, where
$A := 2R_\cA S_w + c$ and
$B := 4 C_{\mathrm{sub}} S_w R_\cA \sqrt{\log(2d/\delta)}$ with
$C_{\mathrm{sub}} = \Theta(d)$ from
Corollary~\ref{cor:projector_conf}. Then, with probability at least
$1-\delta$,
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\;
\DynReg_T^{(c)}
= \tilO\!\bigl(r\sqrt{K T}\bigr)
+ \tilO\!\bigl(d^{2/3}\,K^{1/3}T^{2/3}\bigr)
+ O(W\,V)
+ O(T\,\Delta_\sigma),\;}
\label{eq:main_bound}
\end{equation}
where the first $\tilO$ hides a $\sqrt{L_T}$ factor with
$L_T=\log(1+(T/K) R_\cA^2/(\lambda r))$ (the per-segment elliptical
potential), $V := \sum_k \sum_{s\in\cI_k, s+1\in\cI_k}\|\theta_{s+1}-\theta_s\|_2$
is the within-segment total path variation of $\theta$ ($V=0$ in the
piecewise-constant regime that the bound assumes; the
$O(WV)$ slot is retained symbolically and is non-zero only via the
generalised quantity $V^\dagger$ in
Theorem~\ref{thm:spsc_adaptive}), and
$\delta_\sigma := \hat\sigma^2-\sigma_\varepsilon^2$ is the
variance-plugin error of the probe-moment estimator
(Corollary~\ref{cor:projector_conf}). For isotropic Gaussian probes
with \emph{known rank} $r$, the population bias
$\widetilde B = -\delta_\sigma/(d+2)\,I_d$ is a scaled identity
(Lemma~\ref{lem:G_unbiased_conf}) which preserves eigenvectors
exactly, so $\Delta_\sigma$ contributes only via finite-sample
concentration around the biased mean and is folded into the leading
$\tilO(\cdot)$ constants; the explicit $O(T\Delta_\sigma)$ term is
retained for non-Gaussian probes (Remark~\ref{rem:general_probes})
or for the rank-adaptive corollary, where absolute eigenvalue
thresholds depend on the bias level. The variance-plugin parameter
$\sigma_\varepsilon^2$ is treated as known throughout the main
analysis; we discuss residual-based estimation in
\S\ref{app:concentration_proof}. The four terms in
\eqref{eq:main_bound} correspond to (i) projected exploitation in
$\R^r$ summed across $K$ segments ($\sqrt K$ from
$\sum_k\sqrt{n_k}\le\sqrt{KT}$); (ii) probe--subspace tradeoff from
balancing $cm_k$ against $O(d/\sqrt{m_k})$ subspace-error, aggregated
via Jensen ($\sum_k \ell_k^{2/3}\le K^{1/3}T^{2/3}$); (iii)
boundary-jump drift cost (vanishes in the piecewise-constant
within-segment regime; non-zero in the SPSC-Adaptive extension); (iv)
variance-misspec bias floor (zero for Gaussian probes with known
rank). Proof in \S\ref{app:proof_main}
(concentration in \S\ref{app:concentration_proof}).
\end{theorem}

\begin{remark}[General probe distributions]
\label{rem:general_probes}
For non-Gaussian probe distributions satisfying the assumptions of
\S\ref{sec:setting}, the last term of \eqref{eq:main_bound} inflates
to $O(T\,\Delta_\sigma)$ with
$\Delta_\sigma := 4(|\delta_\sigma|L^2 + 2L^3\epsilon_\times)/\lambda_{\min}$
(conservative bound; Corollary~\ref{cor:projector_conf}). Gaussian probes
are the default because isotropic Gaussian draws yield the sharp
scaled-identity bias (Lemma~\ref{lem:G_unbiased_conf}), and they are
natural in most settings where random exploration is permitted.
\end{remark}

The leading $\tilO(r\sqrt{KT})$ exploitation beats ambient
$\tilO(d\sqrt{KT})$ for $r\ll d$. The bound is sublinear for
$K=o(\min\{T/r^{2},\,T/d\})$ and $V = o(r\sqrt{KT}/W)$. The
analysis-predicted crossover with LinUCB is
$d-r\gtrsim d^{2/3}(T/K)^{1/6}$ (reducing to $d\gtrsim\sqrt{T/K}$ for
$r\to 0$); we verify the crossover empirically in
\S\ref{sec:experiments}.

When $r$ is unknown, thresholding $\widehat M_k$ at the
algorithm-computable level $2\tau_k^\star = 2(\tau_k+b)$
(full Freedman radius $\tau_k$ + bias-shift correction
$b=|\delta_\sigma|/(d+2)$, in raw eigenvalue units) recovers the
true rank w.p.\ $\ge 1-2\delta$ provided $\lambda_{\min}\ge 4\tau_k^\star$;
the bound \eqref{eq:main_bound} applies unchanged. Formal statement
and proof: Corollary~\ref{cor:rank_adaptive} in
Appendix~\ref{app:proof_adaptive_rank}.

\begin{theorem}[SPSC-Adaptive]
\label{thm:spsc_adaptive}
SPSC-Adaptive (Alg.~\ref{alg:spsc_adaptive}) replaces oracle segment
boundaries with an online change detector and uses Bernoulli probe
rate $\mu = c_\mu(K/T)^{1/3}$. Under detector-separation
$\Delta_k\ge 2b$ and admissible detection window
$8\log(K/\delta')\le W_{\mathrm{det}}=o((T/K)^{1/3})$, with probability
$\ge 1-\delta-\delta_{\mathrm{FA}}-\delta'$,
\[
\DynReg_T^{(c)} = \tilO(r\sqrt{KT}) + \tilO(d^{2/3}K^{1/3}T^{2/3})
+ O(W V^\dagger) + O(T\Delta_\sigma) + O\!\bigl(K W_{\mathrm{det}}/\mu\bigr),
\]
where $V^\dagger := V+R_\cA S_w\sum_k\Delta_k\mathbf 1\{\Delta_k<2b\}\ell_k/W$
(the $R_\cA S_w$ factor converts the projector difference $\Delta_k$
into a parameter-norm scale comparable to $V$) absorbs below-threshold
changes; detection failure shifts cost between
sublinear terms (no linear-regret regime), and the bound strictly
recovers Theorem~\ref{thm:spsc_regret} when $V^\dagger=V$, up to a
lower-order detection-delay overhead. Only macroscopic $K,T$ enter the
algorithm; per-segment $\ell_k$ are learned online (and unknown $K$
is handled by a standard doubling extension,
Appendix~\ref{app:adaptive_algo}). Proof: Appendix~\ref{app:proof_adaptive}.
\end{theorem}

\begin{theorem}[Lower bound matching in $T$ on the probe-acquisition term]
\label{thm:spsc_lb}
Let $\Pi$ denote the class of (history-adapted) policies that play
bounded exploit actions $x_t\in\cA=\{x:\|x\|\le R_\cA\}$ and, on any
probe round, draw $x_t=u_t\sim\mathcal N(0,I_d)$. The supremum below
is taken over a class of instances $\nu$ in which the reward
parameter $\theta_t$ is rank-$\le r$ piecewise constant on each
segment but \emph{not} required to satisfy A1--A4 of the upper-bound
setup: the LB construction uses a Le Cam two-point family
$\{\nu_0:\theta\equiv 0,\ \nu_1(v):\theta\equiv\alpha v\}$, and
$\nu_0$ is a degenerate (zero-signal) instance which is invariant
under any policy. Since adding A1--A4 only restricts the supremum
class (an LB on a smaller class is at most an LB on a larger one),
the bound applies a fortiori to instances satisfying the upper-bound
hypotheses. There exist constants $c_0,d_0,T_0>0$ depending only on
$R_\cA,\sigma_\varepsilon,c$ such that for $d\ge d_0\, T^{1/3}$ and
$T\ge T_0$,
\[
\inf_{\pi\in\Pi} \sup_\nu\ \E^\pi_\nu[\DynReg_T^{(c)}]
 \;\ge\; c_0\,c^{1/3}\,(R_\cA\sigma_\varepsilon)^{2/3}\,T^{2/3}.
\]
$\Pi$ contains SPSC (which probes with isotropic Gaussian draws) and
every non-probing algorithm we benchmark against (LinUCB, D-LinUCB,
SW-LinUCB, LinTS, LowOFUL, VOFUL, BOSS, Jedra, LowRank-Reward;
trivially in $\Pi$ at $m{=}0$), so the LB applies uniformly across the
empirical comparison; no projection-class restriction is needed.
Combined with Theorem~\ref{thm:spsc_regret}, SPSC is rate-optimal in
$T$ on the probe-acquisition term. The \emph{hard-projection class}
$\Pi_{\mathrm{HP}} := \{\pi : x_t = \widehat P_t x_t\text{ for all
exploit rounds}\}$ contains policies that constrain exploit actions
to a learned subspace projection $\widehat P_t$; matching the leading
$r\sqrt{KT}$ exploit-regret term outside $\Pi_{\mathrm{HP}}$ and
tightness of the residual $d^{2/3}$ probe-term prefactor remain open.
Proof in \S\ref{app:proof_lb}.
\end{theorem}

%% ============================================================
\section{Experiments}
\label{sec:experiments}

We evaluate SPSC and SPSC-Adaptive on \textbf{nine principal
benchmarks}: a synthetic phase-transition grid (\S\ref{sec:exp_phase}),
six UCI/MovieLens environments (Covertype, Pendigits, Satimage,
MNIST, Fashion-MNIST, MovieLens; \S\ref{sec:exp_real}), and two
semi-synthetic clinical datasets (Warfarin and Vancomycin;
\S\ref{sec:exp_warfarin}). Two additional protocols probe specific
modeling questions: the Russac nonstationary stress test
(\S\ref{sec:exp_russac}) and Open Bandit production logs
(\S\ref{sec:exp_openbandit}, replayed on the random-policy slice of
the public Open Bandit Dataset~\citep{saito2020open}). We compare
against eleven baselines:
LinUCB~\citep{abbasi2011improved}, D-LinUCB~\citep{russac2019weighted},
SW-LinUCB~\citep{cheung2019learning},
Restart-LinUCB~\citep{garivier2011upper}, LowRank-Reward,
LowOFUL~\citep{jun2019bilinear}, VOFUL~\citep{kim2022improved},
LinTS~\citep{agrawal2013thompson}, SW-LinTS, and two adapted
stationary low-rank methods (BOSS, Jedra~\citep{pmlr-v235-jedra24a}).
Oracle-LinUCB (given the true subspace) is included as an
\emph{optimistic oracle reference}, not a lower bound: minimax-optimal
oracle policies can in principle do better. All curves report means
over at least $10$ seeds with $\pm 1$\,SE bands. We report two regret
quantities: \emph{costed regret} $\DynReg^{(c)}_T$ (the formal
metric, action-gap regret on exploit rounds plus the probe cost
$cm$) and \emph{control regret} $\sum_{t\notin\cTprobe}\Delta_t$
(the action-gap component, exclusive of $cm$, directly comparable to
non-probing baselines). SPSC's probe overhead is typically a few
percent of total regret (e.g., $0.9\%$ on Russac, $\sim 3$--$4\%$ on
Warfarin and synthetic at $T{=}5{,}000$), so the two quantities are
close.

\emph{Benchmark protocol.}
We follow the \emph{standard nonstationary-bandit benchmark
protocol} of \citet{russac2019weighted} and
\citet{cheung2019learning}: nonstationarity is induced on real
feature data via cohort/class-subset shifts, the prevailing empirical
convention in nonstationary linear bandits. We additionally include
the Warfarin clinical benchmark (Appendix~\ref{app:warfarin_ablation}),
which carries genuine patient-level heterogeneity from clinical data.
SPSC's lead is monotone in the action-set size and stable across
segmentation rules (omitted for space).

\subsection{Phase-transition boundary}
\label{sec:exp_phase}

Theory predicts a crossover in $(d,r)$ space: SPSC wins where
$d-r$ is large enough that the rank-$r$ exploitation term
$r\sqrt{KT}$ plus the probe term beats ambient
$d\sqrt{KT}$. Verified on a piecewise low-rank LDS benchmark,
$T{=}5{,}000$, $(d,r)\in\{5,\ldots,100\}\times\{1,\ldots,20\}$,
$K{=}10$ segments, $\sigma_\varepsilon=0.3$, $40$ actions,
probe cost $c{=}0.1$.

\begin{figure}[!htbp]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.86\textwidth]{experiment1_synthetic_phase.png}
  \caption{\textbf{Phase-transition boundary.} SPSC/LinUCB costed-regret
  ratio across the $(d,r)$ grid (10 seeds per cell). Black solid
  contour: empirical ratio $=1$. The analysis predicts SPSC wins
  whenever $d-r$ exceeds a threshold growing as $d^{2/3}(T/K)^{1/6}$
  (Theorem~\ref{thm:spsc_regret}); the empirical boundary is
  monotone in the predicted direction.}
  \label{fig:synthetic-phase}
\end{figure}

SPSC achieves $13$--$34\%$ reductions in the SPSC-wins region, with
the ratio falling well below 1 for $d\gtrsim 30$ across all $r\le 20$.

\subsection{Real-data multi-baseline comparison}
\label{sec:exp_real}

We run a $(d,r)$-grid on six real-data benchmarks recast as
piecewise low-rank bandits: UCI \textbf{Covertype}
($K{=}4$, $T{=}10{,}000$), \textbf{Pendigits}, \textbf{Satimage}
($K{=}10$, $T{=}5{,}000$), pixelized \textbf{MNIST} and
\textbf{Fashion-MNIST} ($K{=}10$, $T{=}5{,}000$, random-projection
features), and \textbf{MovieLens-100K} with genuine user ratings as
reward ($K{=}10$, $T{=}5{,}000$). Segments are induced by class- or
user-subset shifts. All runs use 10 seeds. Table~\ref{tab:realdata}
summarises SPSC vs.\ LinUCB and vs.\ best non-oracle competitor
ratios across representative cells; Appendix~\ref{app:percell}
reports the full per-cell tables with mean\,$\pm$\,SE for every
baseline.

