At the best cell $(d{=}105, r{=}10)$, SPSC-Adaptive beats LinUCB by
$-35\%$ on Pendigits and $-60\%$ on Satimage (where the closest
non-oracle baseline trails SPSC-Adaptive by $+42\%$ in regret); at
$(d{=}105, r{=}20)$ on Covertype it beats Restart-LinUCB by $-15\%$.
Non-low-rank baselines are by construction $r$-insensitive.
SPSC wins against every non-oracle baseline on the majority of
Satimage's 16 $(d,r)$ cells; SPSC achieves a $6\%$ average control-regret
reduction over the closest competitor (SW-LinUCB), with per-cell
tables in Appendix~\ref{app:percell}.

\subsection{Clinical drug dosing: Warfarin and Vancomycin}
\label{sec:exp_warfarin}

\paragraph{Warfarin.} Warfarin dosing depends on patient demographics,
genotype (VKORC1, CYP2C9), and clinical indicators with documented
low-rank pharmacogenomic structure~\citep{international2009estimation}.
We construct a semi-synthetic bandit calibrated to IWPC cohort
statistics ($\sim$5,700 patients, $d{=}93$, $K{=}8$ subpopulation
segments, $T{=}5{,}000$, 10 seeds). The data is only
\emph{approximately} low rank (empirical subspace error $0.96$--$1.00$),
so this is a stringent stress-test of the approximate-rank robustness
verified at main-text scale by Table~\ref{tab:assumption_master}.

\begin{table}[!htbp]
\centering
\caption{\textbf{Warfarin} representative cell ($r{=}3$). SPSC-Adaptive
reduces regret by $67.3\%$ vs.\ LinUCB and beats the best non-oracle
competitor (LowOFUL); per-cell tables in Appendix~\ref{app:warfarin_ablation}.}
\label{tab:warfarin_body}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lrr}
\toprule
Method & Costed regret & vs.\ LinUCB \\
\midrule
Oracle LinUCB                           & $177 \pm 4$    & $-91.2\%$\\
\textbf{SPSC Alg.\,1 (ours)}            & $1372 \pm 33$  & $-31.6\%$\\
\textbf{SPSC-Adaptive (ours)}           & $\mathbf{657 \pm 39}$   & $\mathbf{-67.3\%}$\\
LowOFUL~\citep{jun2019bilinear}         & $683 \pm 97$   & $-66.0\%$\\
VOFUL~\citep{kim2022improved}           & $779 \pm 93$   & $-61.2\%$\\
LowRank-Reward                          & $1056 \pm 40$  & $-47.4\%$\\
SW-LinUCB~\citep{cheung2019learning}    & $2096 \pm 18$  & $+4.5\%$\\
LinUCB~\citep{abbasi2011improved}       & $2006 \pm 17$  & ---\\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

A random-subspace ablation (Appendix~\ref{app:warfarin_ablation})
decomposes the gain: roughly half from dimensionality reduction
($\sqrt r$ vs.\ $\sqrt d$), half from the \emph{learned} subspace,
which captures $2$--$6\times$ more signal variance than a random
rank-$r$ projection.

\paragraph{Vancomycin.} A second clinical drug confirms the pattern.
Using the AUC-targeted \citet{rybak2020therapeutic} dosing protocol
(Cockcroft--Gault $\mathrm{CrCl}\to\mathrm{CL}_{\mathrm{vanco}}{=}0.04\,\mathrm{CrCl}\to$ daily dose at AUC$_{24}{=}500$, $d{=}93$, $K{=}8$, 10 seeds),
SPSC-Adaptive reduces control regret by $-36\%$ at $r{=}1$ and $-22\%$
at $r{=}3$ vs.\ LinUCB, beating the best non-oracle competitor at every
rank.

\subsection{Standard nonstationary benchmark (Russac et al., 2019)}
\label{sec:exp_russac}

On the standard small-$d$ stress test ($d{=}2$, $r{=}1$, $K{=}4$,
$T{=}6{,}000$, 50 arms, 30 seeds), SPSC reduces regret by
$\mathbf{-46.5\%}$ vs.\ D-LinUCB, $-34.8\%$ vs.\ SW-LinUCB, and
$\mathbf{-51.6\%}$ vs.\ stationary OFUL (which itself trails
D-LinUCB by $+11.5\%$ on this nonstationary benchmark). Full table
in Appendix~\ref{app:sota_compare}.

\subsection{Comparison with adapted stationary low-rank methods}
\label{sec:exp_boss_jedra}

Stationary low-rank methods (LowOFUL, BOSS~\citep{duong2024boss},
Jedra~\citep{pmlr-v235-jedra24a}) assume fixed subspace; we adapt
BOSS/Jedra with oracle segment-boundary restarts (an advantage SPSC
lacks) on a piecewise-LDS grid ($K{=}10$, $T{=}5{,}000$, 40 actions,
10 seeds, $c{=}0.1$; $d\in\{55,105,200\}\times r\in\{5,10,20\}$). SPSC
wins every cell by $6$--$20\%$, largest at small $d$ (e.g.,
$d{=}55,r{=}10$: $471\pm 10$ vs.\ BOSS $588\pm 27$, Jedra
$602\pm 24$); the lead narrows to $6$--$8\%$ at $d{=}200$ as
oracle-restart-plus-PCA closes the gap, but SPSC retains a uniform
edge without oracle boundaries.

\subsection{Real exploration logs: Open Bandit Pipeline (ZOZO)}
\label{sec:exp_openbandit}

The \citet{saito2020open} Open Bandit Dataset ships production
exploration logs (logged action, propensity, 0/1 click from
ZOZOTOWN; random-policy slice, $T{=}5{,}000$, $K{=}10$, 10 seeds).
At $d{=}55$, $r{=}5$: SPSC reaches $\mathbf{83\pm 2}$ vs.\ LinUCB's
$102\pm 1$ ($-18.8\%$); SPSC-Adaptive at $-10.9\%$. At $d{=}105$ both
SPSC variants tie LinUCB ($\pm 3\%$), consistent with the predicted
$(d,r)$-crossover (Theorem~\ref{thm:spsc_regret}). Tables in
Appendix~\ref{app:percell}.

%% ============================================================
\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

SPSC closes a structural gap in the linear-bandit literature: low-rank
exploitation and changing-subspace adaptation were incompatible under
single-play scalar feedback, because a scalar reward is a rank-one
measurement that cannot identify the active subspace through passive
exploration. We resolve this by pricing a probe channel and routing
its feedback through the lifted moment
$\E[(u^\top M u)\,uu^\top] = \mathcal K(\widetilde M_t)$, turning
rank-one rewards into matrix-valued samples whose eigenstructure is
recovered exactly under isotropic Gaussian probes (scaled-identity
bias). The three probe-side conditions are individually necessary
(Propositions~\ref{prop:nonid_a}--\ref{prop:nonid_c}), so the
assumptions are the weakest under which the problem is solvable at
all.

SPSC attains costed dynamic regret
$\tilO(r\sqrt{KT})+\tilO(d^{2/3}K^{1/3}T^{2/3})$ (piecewise-constant
regime, sample-variance estimation; full 4-term bound in
Theorem~\ref{thm:spsc_regret}), replacing ambient $d$ with intrinsic
rank $r$ in the leading term; a CUSUM-style adaptive variant matches
this rate without oracle changepoints, and a matching
$\Omega(c^{1/3}T^{2/3})$ lower bound (no projection-class restriction)
closes the $T$-rate on the probe term. Across nine synthetic,
real-data, and clinical benchmarks, SPSC reduces regret over LinUCB
and the strongest non-oracle baselines wherever the
$(d,r)$-crossover $d-r\gtrsim d^{2/3}(T/K)^{1/6}$ holds, on both
exactly rank-$r$ and approximately low-rank subspaces.

