\subsection{Assumption-violation study}
\label{app:assumption_violation}

We test the three probe-side conditions at the main-text scale
($d{=}60$, $r{=}5$, $K{=}10$, $T{=}5{,}000$), plus a spectral-radius
sweep that probes the stable-LDS assumption.
Sweeps: (a) variance misspecification $\hat\sigma^2/\sigma_\varepsilon^2
\in\{0.5,1,2,4\}$; (b) approximate-rank perturbation magnitude
$\epsilon_k^\perp\in\{0,0.05,0.1,0.2,0.4\}$ (orthogonal component added
to $\theta_t$); (c) spectral radius $\rho(A_k)\in\{0.8,0.95,0.99,1.0\}$.
Results in Table~\ref{tab:assumption_master}. Variance misspec is
absorbed into a scaled-identity bias (Lemma~\ref{lem:G_unbiased_conf}),
so the \emph{relative} gap (SPSC/Oracle) stays flat even as absolute
regret grows with $\hat\sigma^2$ (ratio $1.27\to 1.16$ as the misspec
ratio sweeps $0.5\to 4$); approximate rank degrades regret near-linearly
in $\epsilon_k^\perp n_k$; SPSC remains well-behaved through $\rho=0.99$
and degrades gracefully at $\rho=1$, outside the stable-LDS assumption
(SPSC-Adaptive $2813\pm59$ vs.\ LinUCB $4644\pm90$ at the random-walk limit).

